{"title_page": "2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on social media", "text_new": "{{Lead too short|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Impact of COVID-19}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' is the first global [[pandemic]] to occur during the proliferation<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Reminds Us: Social Media Is Good, Actually |url=https://reason.com/2020/03/16/covid-19-reminds-us-social-media-is-good-actually/ |website=Reason.com |accessdate=26 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=March 2020}} of social media use, and has affected websites and networks by way of [[Internet meme]]s as well as videos and posts about it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Facebook struggles with high traffic as world sits at home and takes to social media because of Covid-19 |url=https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/other/facebook-struggles-with-high-traffic-as-world-sits-at-home-and-takes-to-social-media-because-of-covid-19/ar-BB11Gra4 |website=www.msn.com |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Okwodu |first1=Janelle |title=\"We Need Joy to Survive\": Naomi Shimada on How to Mindfully Use Social Media in the Age of Social Distancing |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/naomi-shimada-mixed-feelings-social-media-interview |website=Vogue |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nPandemics such as the 1918 [[Spanish flu]] and the 2010s cases of [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] are often compared to the recent coronavirus pandemic<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reich |first1=Samuel |title=How does COVID-19 coronavirus compare to the 1918 Spanish flu? |url=https://www.news-medical.net/news/20200309/How-does-COVID-19-coronavirus-compare-to-the-1918-Spanish-flu.aspx |website=News-Medical.net |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=en |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> (although there has been debate on the similarity between the 1918 flu and the 2020 virus<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |title=Why we should stop comparing the Covid-19 coronavirus outbreak to the 1918 Spanish flu |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/9/21164957/covid-19-spanish-flu-mortality-rate-death-rate |website=Vox |accessdate=26 March 2020 |language=en |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>), however the use of the internet and social media reportedly sets this apart from the rest.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Censorship==\nIn Turkey, more than 400 people were arrested for posting \"provocative\" messages about the pandemic on social media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-turkey-idUSKBN21C1SG|title=Turkey rounds up hundreds for social media posts about coronavirus|newspaper=Reuters|date=March 25, 2020|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\n''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' has called the coronavirus pandemic \"the first true social-media 'infodemic'\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/615184/the-coronavirus-is-the-first-true-social-media-infodemic/|title=The coronavirus is the first true social-media \"infodemic\"|first=Karen|last=Hao|website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/615368/facebook-twitter-social-media-infodemic-misinformation/|title=Here's how social media can combat the coronavirus 'infodemic'|first=Joan|last=Donovan|website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref>\n\nFacebook, Twitter, and YouTube have all increased reliance on [[spam filter]]s because staff members who [[Moderation system|moderate content]] were unable to work.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.wired.com/story/coronavirus-social-media-automated-content-moderation/|title=Coronavirus Disrupts Social Media's First Line of Defense|journal=Wired|via=www.wired.com}}</ref>\n\n[[National Geographic]] has reported on an increased level of \"fake animal news\" on social media during the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/2020/03/coronavirus-pandemic-fake-animal-viral-social-media-posts/|title=Fake animal news abounds on social media as coronavirus upends life|date=March 20, 2020|website=Animals}}</ref>\n\n==Memes==\nMany Internet memes have been created about the pandemic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/uk/culture/a31693127/coronavirus-covid-19-memes-tweets-jokes/|title=These Coronavirus Memes Will Make Life Feel A Little Bit Better|first=Tom|last=Nicholson|date=March 19, 2020|website=Esquire}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6688866/19-covid-19-memes-to-get-you-through-the-weekend/|title=19 COVID-19 memes to get you through the weekend|first=James|last=Joyce|date=March 20, 2020|website=The Canberra Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/trending-in-india/coronavirus-modi-announces-janata-curfew-twitter-reacts-with-memes-and-jokes-6323555/|title=Memes, jokes on social media after PM Modi announces 'Janata Curfew' to slow Covid-19 spread|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ghen C\u00f4 Vy]]\n*[[Safe Hands Challenge]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |last1=Ouyang |first1=Helen |title=At the Front Lines of Coronavirus, Turning to Social Media |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/18/well/live/coronavirus-doctors-facebook-twitter-social-media-covid.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 18, 2020}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Adam |title=Facebook and Instagram to Limit Coronavirus Misinformation |journal=Entrepreneur |date=31 January 2020 |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/345770}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Carman |first1=Ashley |title=Instagram cracks down on coronavirus AR effects |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/13/21179055/instagram-augmented-reality-effect-coronavirus-covid-19 |work=The Verge |date=March 13, 2020}}\n* [https://www.cbsnews.com/video/social-medias-role-in-spreading-coronavirus-misinformation/ Coronavirus misinformation on social media], [[CBS News]]\n* [https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-25/how-to